  <static seed="1289" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/complexFractions10.pg">
    <statement><p>Calculate the following. Use an improper fraction in your answer.</p>
<p><ol label="a.">
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{ \frac{20}{3} }{ \frac{5}{4} } =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{ \frac{r}{t} }{ \frac{x}{y} } =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{16}{3}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{ry}{tx}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><alert>Problem 1</alert></p>
<p>To simplify a complex fraction, we find the common denominator of all fractions. In this case, it is <m>12</m>. We multiply the complex fraction<rsq/>s numerator and denominator by this common denominator, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
    
      \amp = \frac{ \frac{20}{3} \cdot 12 }{ \frac{5}{4} \cdot 12 } \\
      \amp = \frac{ 80 }{ 15 } \\
      \amp = {{\frac{16}{3}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Here is a simple way to do fraction multiplication:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \frac{20}{3} \cdot 12 = 12 \div 3 \cdot 20 = 80 }</m></p>
<p><alert>Problem 2</alert></p>
<p>To simplify a complex fraction, we find the common denominator of all fractions. In this case, it is <m>{ty}</m>. We multiply the complex fraction<rsq/>s numerator and denominator by this common denominator, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
    
      \amp = \frac{ \frac{r}{t} \cdot {ty} }{ \frac{x}{y} \cdot {ty} } \\
      \amp = {\frac{ry}{tx}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
